  <div>
    <textarea class="terms" readonly="readonly">Acting Like A Kid Policies
      Behavior Policy
      We do not expect students to be perfect, remember every single line, or be Brad Pitt or Idina Menzel.  We do, however, have FIVE simple rules that must be followed in our class and we expect every student to know these rules and abide by them.
      Be respectful.  Students must treat others the way they want to be treated.  In this class, students will be singing, acting, and dancing. Performing requires vulnerability and we want to create a comfortable and encouraging environment.
      Keep hands, feet, and other objects to yourself unless otherwise directed. We want to create a safe environment.  There will be a lot of movement and dancing in this class and we will be teaching choreography and stage direction with props.  Students are not allowed to grab objects, touch each other, jump, or run in the room, unless we have given specific instructions to do so.
      Follow the direction the FIRST time asked.  It goes without saying that if this rule is followed, there will be more time to have fun and less time giving directions.
      Raise your hand and WAIT for permission to speak.  Every idea and question is important in our class.  If students are calling out and not waiting their turn, then ideas and questions will be missed.
      Do your best!  We understand that we may ask some strange requests and that everyone has their own personal “best.”  “I don’t want to” is NOT an option in this class unless an acceptable reason is given.
      REWARDS!
      We will give out stickers and rewards for good behavior.   Students will receive a sticker for remembering to bring back their script every week, throughout the class when rules are being followed, and for any stand out behavior that goes above and beyond what is required.  After 10 stickers, students will be able to receive a PRIZE!

      CONSEQUENCES
      Students will receive warnings if rules are not being followed.  After THREE warnings there will be consequences.  After a third warning, students will be required to write a reflection about their behavior.  This reflection will be sent home for parents to sign and bring back to class.  If a behavior is still an issue after a student has filled out THREE reflections, the student may be asked to leave class and not return.
    </textarea>
     <p>
      <%= f.label :behavior_policy  %>:
      <%= radio_button_tag(:behavior_consent, "I Agree") %>
      <%= label_tag(:behavior_consent, "I Agree") %>
      <%= radio_button_tag(:behavior_consent, "I Disagree") %>
      <%= label_tag(:behavior_consent, "I Disagree") %>
    </p>
